</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6ADEBA7C9E060E084AC62DC25E15A252" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" type="notes">
<paragraph id="6C7C96B77C6C130E57C205574122EA9E" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="272D465A3A1E571875E018A4214D42EB" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">
At present, 
<taxonomicName id="DBA01696CBFA9701DF1A360BAAAAC943" family="Drepanidae" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. quinaria" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="quinaria">
<emphasis id="50C00FAB6B2850C5783B80B88E3C4C57" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">D. quinaria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
comprises five subspecies; four are recorded from China, the exception being 
<taxonomicName id="F68EED844373EA106AB6787949CFB093" family="Drepanidae" genus="D." kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="D. quinaria subsp. nivea" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="subSpecies" species="quinaria" subSpecies="nivea">
<emphasis id="25489BBD11CA1E142ECA790744DEE6A1" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">D. quinaria nivea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Hampson), which is distributed in India.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
